# .NET API Conventions

Assume **ASP.NET Core Web API** (.NET 9/10) with attribute-routed controllers or Minimal API endpointsŌĆömatch existing project style.

## Controller / endpoint design

- Keep **action methods thin**; delegate to services or use-case handlers (MediatR, or plain service classes).
- Use **explicit** route attributes, `[ApiController]`, `[ProducesResponseType]`, and `Produces<T>` for stable, self-documenting contracts.
- Prefer **constructor injection** via `IServiceCollection` for repositories, services, and `IOptions<T>` settings.
- Apply `[Authorize]` / policy-based authorization at the controller or action level; enforce business-rule checks inside services.

## HTTP verbs & status codes

- `GET` ŌåÆ **200** with body, or **404** when a single resource is missing.
- `POST` ŌåÆ **201 Created** with `Location` header when creating a resource; **409 Conflict** for duplicates.
- `PUT` / `PATCH` ŌåÆ **200** or **204 No Content**.
- `DELETE` ŌåÆ **204** or **404**.
- Use `ActionResult<T>` or `Results<TŌĆ”>` (Minimal API) for typed returns and accurate OpenAPI generation.

## Validation & models

- Use **Data Annotations** (`[Required]`, `[MaxLength]`, `[Range]`) or **FluentValidation** for request models; `[ApiController]` triggers automatic 400 responses on model-state errors.
- Use **record types** or dedicated request/response DTOs for API boundariesŌĆönever expose EF Core entities directly.
- Version or extend DTOs for **backward-compatible** changes; document breaking changes in OpenAPI and release notes.
- Validate input at the boundary; use `ModelState.IsValid` guards or action filters.

## Errors

- Return **Problem Details** (RFC 7807) for error responses using `ProblemDetails` or `ValidationProblemDetails`.
- Map unexpected failures to appropriate **5xx** via global exception-handling middleware (`UseExceptionHandler` / `IProblemDetailsService`); never leak stack traces in production.
- Register a consistent `IExceptionHandler` or use `app.UseExceptionHandler(...)` in `Program.cs`.

## OpenAPI / Swagger

- Use **Swashbuckle** (`Swashbuckle.AspNetCore`) or **NSwag** to generate / serve OpenAPI 3.x; keep spec aligned with live behavior (`specs-driven-design.mdc`).
- Annotate with XML doc comments (`///`) and `[ProducesResponseType]` so the generated spec is accurate.
- Include example requests and responses using `SwaggerRequestExample` / `SwaggerResponseExample` where relevant.

## Minimal API (when used)

- Group related endpoints with `RouteGroupBuilder` (`.MapGroup()`).
- Prefer typed `Results<T, T>` returns for correct OpenAPI generation.
- Use endpoint filters (`AddEndpointFilter`) for cross-cutting concerns instead of inline duplication.
